title: For Sale:  crate of 7.62x54 ammo 880rds (2-440rd spam cans)
location: 1730 Oxford St. Worthington, MN 56187, Minnesota, United States
postcontent:
The 7.62×54mmR is a rimmed rifle cartridge developed by the Russian Empire and was introduced as a service cartridge in 1891. Originally designed for the bolt-action Mosin–Nagant rifle, it was used during the late Tsarist era and throughout the Soviet period to the present day. The cartridge remains one of the few standard issue rimmed cartridges still in military use and has the longest service life of all military issued cartridges in the world.[4]

The American Winchester Model 1895 was also chambered for this cartridge per a contract with the Russian government. The 7.62×54mmR is still in use by the Russian military in the Dragunov and other sniper rifles, as well as some modern machine guns like the PKM. Originally, the round was designated as "Трехлинейный патрон образца 1891 года" - (Three-line cartridge model of 1891). It then became widely known under the designation "7,62мм винтовочный патрон" (7,62mm rifle cartridge). The round has erroneously come to be known as the "7.62mm Russian" (and is still often referred to as such colloquially), but, according to new standards, the "R" in the modern official C.I.P. designation (7.62 × 54 R) stands for Rimmed, in line with standard C.I.P. designations. The name is sometimes confused with the "7.62 Soviet" round, which refers to the 7.62×39mm cartridge used in the SKS and AK-based (AK-47) rifles.

This ammunition is for sale in our shop. We accept personal check, money order and credit card. Additional 3% on credit card. This will ship FEDEX for $40 in the continental USA. Thank you. Julie at Pawn It. REDACTED 1730 Oxford St. Worthington, MN 56187

title: For Sale:  Ruger BX-25 X2 10/22 50rd. Magazine - Black
postcontent:
This is a Ruger BX-25 X2 10/22 50rd. Magazine. Ruger came up with an innovative design to couple two magazines together. It comes with a rubber dust cover to prevent the intrusion of dirt and debris for the on deck magazine. Once the first 25rds. are used, all you have to do is remove the dust cover and flip the mag. over. As reliable as the standard BX-1 10-round Ruger rotary magazine. Stainless steel feed lips are designed to present cartridges into the action at a 30 degree angle for better feed reliability. Stainless steel, constant force spring provides feed consistency round after round. Anti-tilt follower is injection molded from a high lubricity polyacetal for consistent reliability. BX-25 X2 magazines will work with any factory original Ruger 10/22 Rifle, SR-22 Rifle, 22 Charger Pistol and 77/22 Rifle. The BX-25 will run reliably with a wide variety of ammunition. However, you may experience malfunctions (“jams”) when using subsonic ammunition or ammunition with heavy coatings of bullet lube. In some instances, cleaning the magazine may improve reliability, but in other cases you may need to switch to a different type or brand of ammunition to get the full use and enjoyment from your BX-25 X2 magazine. Please also be aware that some .22 LR magazine loaders are prone to damaging cartridges. If you experience stoppages while using magazines that were loaded using a magazine loader, please try loading the magazines by hand and determine if reliability improves. The BX-25 X2 magazine requires no lubrication. If it becomes necessary to clean the magazine, loosen the screws on the right and left side of the magazine with a 3/32’’ hex tool. Next, separate the two halves, lifting the right side from the left side, and then lift out the spring, throat and follower from the left side. To reassemble the magazine, reverse the order of the disassembly instructions.

High Capacity Magazine Restrictions: High capacity magazines are legal in some areas of the U.S. Please be aware of your local laws before ordering. We will not ship magazines to the State of New York. We will not ship magazines with a capacity above 10 rounds to California. We will not ship magazines with a capacity above 20 rounds to City of Denver, Colorado. It's up to the customer to comply with all laws regarding these items.
